<p>May 10, 2012<br /><strong>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE</strong><br />
  Contact: Julie Holmquist  952-838-9000, <a href="mailto:julie.holmquist@PACER.org">julie.holmquist@PACER.org</a></p>
<h2><strong>Nationally-syndicated &ldquo;e-Town&rdquo; radio program presents achievement award for bullying prevention to PACER Center&rsquo;s Paula Goldberg</strong></h2>
<p>PACER  Center Executive Director Paula Goldberg recently received the &lsquo;E-Chievement  Award&rsquo; in recognition of PACER&rsquo;s national bullying prevention efforts. The  award is presented by the syndicated &ldquo;e-Town&rdquo; radio program based in Boulder,  Colo., which educates, entertains, and inspires its audience through live music  and conversation. Nominated by listeners, winners are cited for making a  positive difference in their communities and beyond. The pre-recorded episode featuring  the award presentation will air May 16-22 on 300 stations across North America.</p>
<p>  Goldberg  is a founder of PACER Center in Minneapolis, a national parent center that has  been serving families of children and young adults with any disability since 1978.  PACER provides individual assistance, workshops, publications, and other  resources to help families make decisions about education and other services  for their child or young adult with disabilities.</p>
<p>  Founded  in 2006, PACER&rsquo;s National Bullying Prevention Center serves all children,  including those with disabilities. It unites, engages, and educates communities  nationwide to address bullying through creative, relevant, interactive  resources. In 2006, PACER also developed National Bullying Prevention Month in  October. The center&rsquo;s award-winning websites each serve a specific audience:</p>
<ul type="disc">
  <li><strong>PACERKidsAgainstBullying.org &ndash; </strong>elementary school children<strong></strong></li>
  <li><strong>PACERTeensAgainstBullying.org &ndash; </strong>middle and high school       students </li>
  <li><strong>PACER.org/bullying</strong> &ndash; parents, educators, and       other adults</li>
</ul>
<p>Information  on the &ldquo;e-Town&rdquo; broadcast, and a list of stations that will carry it, is  available at etown.org. For more information on the work of PACER&rsquo;s National  Bullying Prevention Center, visit PACER.org/bullying.</p>
